  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "It's important to place these moments in their social/historical context for greater understanding. "
        },
        {
          "text": "Please review the following:",
          "bold": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "What is happening around this time? ",
          "bold": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulleted-list",
      "children": [
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "October 1, 1962: James Meredith became the first Black student to attend the University of Mississippi in 1962, desegregating the university and setting off a series of violent riots in protest."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "1964: "
                },
                {
                  "type": "link",
                  "url": "https://www.crmvet.org/info/mccomb1964.pdf",
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "text": "List of Civil Rights Incidents in McComb, Mississippi"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "text": ", including bombings of Black homes and businesses."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "October 19, 1964: This audio was recorded after a series of protests led to the arrest of a group of black high school students and members of the Council of Federated Organizations (who we hear in the recording after their release)."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "July 2, 1964: The Civil Rights Act of 1964 was signed."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "list-item",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "August 6, 1965: The Voting Rights Act of 1965 went into effect."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "What is criminal syndicalism?",
          "bold": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "https://www.crmvet.org/docs/ms_laws64-c.pdf",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Passed in 1964, "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "“Senate Bill 2027 prohibits ‘criminal syndicalism,’ defined as doctrine or precept which advocates, teaches or aids and abets the commission of crime…violence and force…as a means of accomplishing or affecting a change in agricultural or industrial ownership or control. or in affecting any political or social change or for profit. Any person who \"advocates, instigates, suggests, teaches, etc.  ‘criminal syndicalism’ or '’’attempts to justify it’ is guilty of a felony.” "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Who is John Beecher?",
          "bold": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "John Beecher was a descendant of the author Harriet Beecher Stowe and was a poet, civil rights activist, and journalist. He speaks in our second lesson clip."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "What is the COFO? ",
          "bold": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The Council of Federated Organizations (COFO) was first formed in 1961 to support jailed Freedom Riders. In 1962, it reorganized to an umbrella organization to avoid inter-organizational conflict and facilitate funds and encourage grassroots activism towards voter education and registration in Mississippi. In the 1960s, COFO field workers (the majority of whom were college-age Mississippians) organized many voter registration projects–as our Beecher recording captures. For more information, see the "
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "https://snccdigital.org/inside-sncc/alliances-relationships/cofo/",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee’s Page on the COFO"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
